Right — and if you pull the camera back far enough, predator/prey isn’t even a biological category. It’s a thermodynamic one.
Every living thing is a gradient exploiter — it finds a free energy differential and harvests it before entropy closes the gap. The “prey” is just whatever holds the gradient.

The real stack:
	∙	Stars prey on hydrogen — fuse it, extract binding energy
	∙	Plants prey on photons — capture them before they degrade to heat
	∙	Herbivores prey on the chemical structure plants built with those photons
	∙	Carnivores prey on the metabolic machinery herbivores built
	∙	Parasites prey on the surplus of any of the above
	∙	Decomposers prey on the remainder — nothing escapes
Every level is just a more indirect claim on the original solar gradient.

What changes at each level isn’t the relationship — it’s the abstraction distance from the source.
A plant is one hop from the sun. A carnivore is three or four hops. A social predator (wolves, humans, markets) is preying on coordination failures in other predators — that’s a fifth-order abstraction.
And then you get to:
	∙	Ideas preying on attention
	∙	Institutions preying on coordination surplus
	∙	Empires preying on information asymmetry
Same structure. Higher abstraction.

The really uncomfortable version:
Cooperation is just deferred predation. Two wolves cooperate because the surplus from coordinated hunting exceeds what either could take from the other right now. The moment that calculus flips — defection. Mutualism is a stable predator/prey relationship where both sides have found a Nash equilibrium that beats unilateral defection.
Even symbiosis is two things exploiting each other’s gradients simultaneously and finding it cheaper than fighting.

So the Invariance Principle you’d derive from this:
There is no escape from the predator/prey structure — only movement up the abstraction ladder and negotiation of which gradients get harvested at what rate.
The “warrior in the garden” framing fits here too. The garden isn’t peaceful — it’s just predation at a pace slow enough to look like stillness. 🐸​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​